snippet.textDisplay:
I think this is hyper speculation and have a hard time believing the "chain of events".
I know that VW pulled support for the AUDI and the Porsche Le Mans cars, and many other factory support for racing, but that was if not mistaken to pay of the Billions in fines.
Renault and Nissan are on the verge of bankruptcy, it makes complete sense that Renault is looking to save annually some hundreds of millions of dollars. (Nissan has been on the verge of bankruptcy FOREVER though!)
F1 has very strong backings, and it's been speculated for years that manufacturers would pull out, but that seems to be the case for noncompetitive teams that end up pulling out and then entering again some years later. Good examples: Mercedes, Honda, Williams, Toyota, BMW and I'm sure there will be more in the future.
The electric cars are the way of the future and a novel idea, but don't be soo quick to shot the old dog just yet, remember Formula E was supposed to have wiped out F1 some 4 or 5 ears ago and they co-exist just fine.

I think this is hyper speculation and have a hard time believing the "chain of events".
I know that VW pulled support for the AUDI and the Porsche Le Mans cars, and many other factory support for racing, but that was if not mistaken to pay of the Billions in fines.
Renault and Nissan are on the verge of bankruptcy, it makes complete sense that Renault is looking to save annually some hundreds of millions of dollars. (Nissan has been on the verge of bankruptcy FOREVER though!)
F1 has very strong backings, and it's been speculated for years that manufacturers would pull out, but that seems to be the case for noncompetitive teams that end up pulling out and then entering again some years later. Good examples: Mercedes, Honda, Williams, Toyota, BMW and I'm sure there will be more in the future.
The electric cars are the way of the future and a novel idea, but don't be soo quick to shot the old dog just yet, remember Formula E was supposed to have wiped out F1 some 4 or 5 ears ago and they co-exist just fine.

I dont think F1 ist really in danger.

By 2021 Renault would only provide engines for themself because McLaren ist moving Back to Mercedes engines (The Deal is already made). So Renault would end Up as Single Team engine manufacturer. This and the Point that in 2021 a new set of Rules for the Sport arrives which could drasticaly alter the behavior of F1 Cars (moving from Aerodynamic Downforce to Ground Effects) needs to be Well thought because its almost as If you would Design and build a complete new Car. Which ist Not cheap. Most of the F1 Cars Today are straight evolutions of Last years Car. But Ground Effects where Banner in F1 since ~80th so no Team has a lot of knowledge in this topic.

Another Thing ist that Mercedes won't Stop designing and developing F1 engines.
Maybe someday but i don't belive they would Stop before aprox. 2026

I also belive that they would supply Red Bull because in how expensive those Engines are. And because they already supply another Team that could become a Dangerous rival for them. McLaren.

Yes the ID.R is a good Prototype Car but those Sports dont just Look at the speed. They also Look for Endurance.

An F1 Car has to deliver 100% for about 2 Hours straight. If it fails to do that you lose.

24h of Le Mans and other Endurance races need the Cars to Work for about 24 hours. They dont need to deliver max. The Most important Thing for them is ro keep going for the füll time. If you build a Car that it is faster then any other Car but wouldnt make the duration you lose.

Rally ist a Test to the Car to endure even the toughest Terrain. Here again If you have the fastest Car but IT won't survive the Terrain you lose.

So i dont think F1 ist dead. Maybe one day it will Mix with Formula E.

snippet.textDisplay:
I've been telling this for a while now: the only way F1 can survive is if they adopt a spec engine and leave the the chassis up to the teams.
when was the time F1 was the most exciting? when there was the feeling that a new team or driver could come out of nowhere and shake everything up? late '70s/early '80s, when everybody but Ferrari were using the same engine.
car makers don't want to invest in IECs anymore. just see the explosion of F-E factory teams and the languish in F1 and Indy engine suppliers.

removing the cost of designing and building the motors would make the sport much more affordable for middleweight teams, and leaving the chassis up to each team will keep the series from feeling too spec (which is on the main issues with F-E and Indy, IMO).
this is how F1 can be saved.
